Part 1: Wrangling

Problem 1

Using SQL compute a relation containing the total payroll and winning percentage

In[75]:
# Include the SQL code used to create this relation
q1= "SELECT Salaries.yearID, Salaries.teamID, Teams.franchID, \
Teams.W as number_of_wins, Teams.G as number_of_games, sum(Salaries.salary) as total_payroll, \
CAST(Teams.W as FLOAT)/CAST(Teams.G as FLOAT)*100 as winning_percentage \
FROM (Salaries INNER JOIN Teams ON Salaries.teamID = Teams.teamID \
AND Salaries.yearID = Teams.yearID) GROUP BY Salaries.yearID, Salaries.teamID"
q1_out = pd.read_sql(q1, conn)
q1_out.head(1)
Out[75]:
yearID teamID franchID number_of_wins number_of_games total_payroll winning_percentage
0 1985 ATL ATL 66 162 14807000.0 40.740741

Describe how you dealt with any missing data in these two relations.

Before the join of these two relations, I've noticed that there are some missing data, but I use inner join to avoid considering those missing data, since inner join only consider the available data. Also inner join helps to reduce the size of data. Therefore, I choose to use inner join. In that case, if there is any missing data in either of the two tables, the line with that missing data will be dropped by default.

Part 3: Data transformations

Standardizing across years

It looks like comparing payrolls across years is problematic so let's do a transformation that will help with these comparisons.

Problem 5

Create a new variable in your dataset that standardizes payroll conditioned on year. It may help to merge salaries and the win percentages tables.

In[90]:
# Create a new variable in your dataset that standardizes payroll conditioned on year.
df['standardized_payroll']=df.groupby('yearID')['total_payroll'].transform(lambda x: (x - x.mean()) / x.std())
In[91]:
# Repeat the same plots as Problem 4, but use this new standardized payroll variable.

In[96]:
# make the scatter plot
fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.scatter(x=df.standardized_payroll, y=df.winning_percentage)
axes = plt.gca()
# add a regression line
m, b = np.polyfit(df.standardized_payroll, df.winning_percentage, 1)
X_plot = np.linspace(axes.get_xlim()[0],axes.get_xlim()[1],100)
plt.plot(X_plot, m*X_plot + b, '-')
Out[96]:
[<matplotlib.lines.Line2D at 0x14e8b2630>]
In[97]:
# check the coefficients we've got
(m,b)
Out[97]:
(2.7478145870693136, 49.98855314843017)

The regression line gives you expected winning percentage as a function of standardized payroll. Looking at the regression line, it looks like teams that spend roughly the average payroll in a given year will win 50% of their games (i.e. win_pct is 50 when standardized_payroll is 0), and teams increase 5% wins for every 2 standard units of payroll (i.e., win_pct is 55 when standardized_payroll is 2). It could be that you get different coefficient. You should use the ones that you compute.

In[99]:
# apply the coefficients to the formula
df['expected_win_pct']=df['standardized_payroll'].apply(lambda x: b+m*x)

Spending efficiency

Using this result, we can now create a single plot that makes it easier to compare teams efficiency. The idea is to create a new measurement unit for each team based on their winning percentage and their expected winning percentage that we can plot across time summarizing how efficient each team is in their spending.

Question 4

What can you learn from this plot compared to the set of plots you looked at in Question 2 and 3? How good was Oakland's efficiency during the Moneyball period?

When I look at the set of plots in Question 2 and 3, I have to look carefully to pick out a point from a scatter plot and then do analysis, while for the plot above, I only need to glance at the corresponding color of line to see the data, which is less time-consuming and more convenient.
In addition, since each plot in Question 2 and Question 3 is scatterplot, which is not as helpful as the line graph above for me to see the trend of efficiency among different years.

Talking about Oakland's efficiency, it was high in 1990, but then it fluctuated and decreased until 1994. After that, it fluctuated until 1998. After 1998, it increases and reaches the highest point after 2003. The efficiency of Oakland A was the highest among all teams during the Moneyball period. After that, it fluctuated until 2012, and then it increased once again to reach a relatively high level. After 2014, it was predicted to decrease. In all, Oakland's efficiency was at the top of all teams during the Moneyball period.
